Veteran South African rapperÂ Ben Sharpa died this morning at age 41 after being hospitalised for complications with diabetes. Sharpa was prominent in the mid-2000s in the local hip hop scene. His music touched on social and political issues in country. His album B. Sharpa, released in 2008 was well acclaimed. The album was released by Cape Town based indie labelÂ Pioneer Unit. From B. Sharpa was the massive street hit "Hegemony". In it the artist rapped about police brutality.   In his prime, Sharpa toured Europe extensively. He performed at festivals such as Rio Loco (FR), Riddim Collision (FR), Paleo (CH), Glastonbury (UK), Dour (BEL) and Extrema (NL). In 2012, he released an album called 4thÂ Density Light ShowÂ (4DLS)Â with the production duoÂ Pure Solid.   The South African hip-hop community is mourning the passing of the legend.  RIP to a SA Hip Hop legend @bensharpa sad news to receive today ğŸ˜”but the music will live forever ğŸ™ğŸ½ #KaptainMyKaptain #RestInRhyme https://t.co/DrFnOs1f11      Damn b, rest in eternal music Ben SharpaâœŠğŸ¾      Woke up to the news my brother @bensharpa is dead.     Just heard sad news about the death of one of the best to ever do it, one of the pioneers of SA Hip Hop, all time fave; Kaptin my Kaptin Ben Sharpa is no more ğŸ˜­ğŸ˜­ğŸ˜­ğŸ™†ğŸ¾â€â™‚ï¸ğŸ™†ğŸ¾â€â™‚ï¸ RIPBenSharpa pic.twitter.com/BdI426acVv      S.A. #hiphop suffered a MASSIVE blow today. ğŸ˜¢ğŸ˜­ Rest in eternal POWER #BenSharpa! One of the greatest to ever drop bars in the southern hemisphere & the only underground cat with a HYPE mag cover.     The Saturday Star 